{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"Vnf1xB0mwxWxtKJvwEOmtagSUDk=","kind":"spec","title":"kref author identity override (env + git config) — design","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958624,"nonce":"dZ1uVOkfRXnNCPkD26M6mSpl7ZU=","body":"# kref author identity override (env + git config) — design\n\n- **Date:** 2026-06-27\n- **Status:** Approved (pending implementation)\n- **Problem:** LLM work runs in containers whose git identity differs from the\n  human's. The human wants their name/email on kref's document history (the\n  logical author) while the underlying **git** objects stay authored by the\n  container's default git identity.\n\n## Key facts (verified)\n\n- kref's logical author is a git-bug **identity** stored inside the op-pack;\n  the git commit author is written separately by `repo.StoreCommit` (git-bug\n  `operation_pack.go:166`) and uses the default git config user. The two are\n  already decoupled — overriding the kref author does **not** touch git commit\n  authorship.\n- Today the author is baked at `kref init` (`identity.SetUserIdentity`) and\n  reloaded by every `store.Open` (`identity.GetUserIdentity`). So it never\n  reflects later env/config changes.\n- `repo.AnyConfig()` reads a **merged global+local** git config (so a global\n  `~/.gitconfig` works). `identity.ReadAllLocal` lists identities for\n  find-or-create; `identity.NewIdentity`+`Commit` creates one.\n\n## Decisions\n\n- **D1 — resolution precedence (highest first):**\n  1. env `KREF_AUTHOR_NAME` + `KREF_AUTHOR_EMAIL`\n  2. git config `kref.author.name` + `kref.author.email` (merged global+local)\n  3. the init-time stored identity (`GetUserIdentity`) — today's behavior\n- **D2 — both fields required per source.** If a source supplies exactly one of\n  name/email, that is an error (\"set both …\"); kref does **not** fill the\n  missing half from a lower layer (avoids a mixed human-name/container-email\n  identity). A source contributes only when it supplies *both*.\n- **D3 — find-or-create.** An override (name,email) resolves to a git-bug\n  identity by scanning `ReadAllLocal` for a name+email match; if none, create and\n  commit a new one. This keeps the identity resolvable for sync and avoids\n  minting a duplicate identity object every run.\n- **D4 — scope.** Resolution happens in `store.Open` (every command). `kref\n  init` is unchanged (it still seeds layer 3 from git user / `--name`/`--email`).\n  The override is orthogonal to `--actor`/`KREF_ACTOR` (provenance human/agent),\n  which is unaffected.\n\n## Components\n\n- `internal/store/store.go`:\n  - `authorOverride(repo) (name, email, source string, err error)` — applies\n    D1/D2; `source` is `\"\"` when no override.\n  - `findOrCreateIdentity(repo, name, email) (*identity.Identity, error)` — D3.\n  - `Open` resolves: if `source != \"\"` use find-or-create; else\n    `GetUserIdentity` (unchanged path/error).\n- Docs: README \"Attribution\" section + a short config note; command reference.\n\n## Testing (TDD, package store)\n\n- env override attributes new entries to the env identity (CreatedBy).\n- git config override (write `kref.author.*` via LocalConfig) attributes to it.\n- env beats git config when both set.\n- partial env (name only / email only) → error; partial git config → error.\n- neither set → falls back to the stored init identity (unchanged behavior).\n- find-or-create reuses an existing identity (no duplicate id across two runs\n  with the same name+email).\n\n## Out of scope (YAGNI)\n\nNo change to `init`, `--actor`, or git commit authorship. No per-tier author. No\nCLI flag for author (env/config only, per the request)."}]}